NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Not playing coded 10s and 9s, you would lead the J from J109, KJ10, and AJ10. Experts feel it is important for the partner of the leader to know whether, on the lead of the J, the leader holds a higher honor besides the jack. So they came up with the idea that the lead of the jack denies a higher honor. (They sometimes call this "jack denies".) So, with a holding of KJ10 and AJ10 you have to lead the 10. |
pg| ***** 52 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It is usually easy for the partner of the leader to figure out whether the leader has the jack and a higher honor or is just leading 10 from top of nothing. If it is top of nothing, the jack is often visible in or the A and K are both visible.  So with the lead of the 10, the other defender can usually figure out when partner has KJ10 or AJ10.|
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But this led to another problem. The standard lead (not playing coded 9s) from A109, K109, and Q109 is the 10. Well, now the 10 is used to show AJ10 or KJ10. So they had to change the lead from A109, K109, and  Q109 to the 9. But if you are an expert, the "jack denies a higher honor" inference is very important.|
